toric walking tour at  the V&A Waterfront|url=http://www.penbev.co.za/uploads/files/PenBev%20Historical%20Walking%20Tour%20Release_FINAL.pdf|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=Press Release|agency=Reputation Matters|publisher=Peninsula Beverage Co (Pty) (Ltd)|date=27 June 2013|location=Cape Town, South Africa|format=pdf}}</ref> military analyst and [[South African Army|citizen soldier]].<ref name=WPCV>{{cite web|last1=Steenkamp|first1=Willem|title=On Parade List|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/onparade/iEKkitUhJ5s|website=Google Groups|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> He has published a number of books and consults widely in military affairs.\n\n==Awards==\n* Cited in 1967 and 1968 in [[United Press International]]'s annual selection of its best news feature articles worldwide.\n* Awarded the Settlers' Prize for Enterprising Journalism in 1982.\n* Awarded the Maskew Miller Prize (co-winner with James Ambrose Brown) in 1983 for the [[Second Boer War|Anglo-Boer War]] novel \"The Blockhouse\".\n* Awarded the Lady Usher Memorial Prize in 1985 for the historical novel \"The Horse Thief\".\n* Awarded the Barcom Prize for Professional Military Writing in 1988 for an essay on future [[Amphibious warfare|amphibious assault]] personnel requirements.\n\n== Appointments ==\n*[[Justice of the peace]] (appointed 1993).\n*[[United Nations|UN]] international election observer (appointed 1994).\n* Member of the Ceremonial Staff Board (advisory body to the [[South African National Defence Force|SANDF]]'s Director of Ceremonial and Military Music) up to 2004.\n* Member of the VOC Foundation.\n\n== Military Service ==\n\n=== List of postings and tasks===\n* 1958: Called up for [[South African Army|Active Citizen Force]] service: Study deferment.\n* 1961{{snd}}1965: Routine non-continuous regimental service.\n* 1966{{snd}}1969: On inactive reserve.\n* 1969{{snd}}1979: Regimental service (training and operational).\n* 1980{{snd}}1983: Seconded to 71 Motorised Brigade staff.\n* 1984{{snd}}1990: Regimental service (training and operational).\n* 1990{{snd}}1992: Seconded to 75 Motorised Brigade/9 SA Division staff.\n* 1993{{snd}}to date: Regimental service, in various capacities: inter alia officer in charge of designing and implementing the wreath-laying at Woltemade Cemetery by [[Elizabeth II|HM Queen Elizabeth II]], 1995.\n* Extra-regimental/staff employment:\n** Secondments to 71 Motorised Brigade and 75 Motorised Brigade/9 SA Division, as noted.\n** Observer on three external operations, 1979{{snd}}1985.\n** Minute-taker/diarist: Operation Sclera (1984 South African{{snd}}Angolan Joint Monitoring Commission).\n** Member/scriba of official [[South African Defence Force|SADF]] delegation sent to attend national convention of United States Reserve Officers' Association at [[Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], July 1993; also visited [[Reserve Officers Association|ROA]] head office in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington DC]] for confidential briefing to convey to SA Minister of Defence\n* 1997{{snd}}1998: Member of the SA National Defence Force's Education, Training and Development Team (with Lt Col A. M. Marriner {{Post-nominals|country=ZAR|JCD}}) revising Reserve Force training\n\n=== Military Awards ===\n* {{Medal Display|MMM}}\n* [[Chief of the Army's Commendation]]\n* {{Medal Display|PP}}\n* {{Medal Display|SAM}}\n* {{Medal Display|GSM}}\n* {{Medal Display|JCD}}\n* {{Medal Display|JCM}}\n* {{Medal Display|Unitas Medal}}\n* {{Badge Display|BRVS|100px}}\n\n== Published Books ==\n* Ngami! (1971). Fictionalised re-telling in Afrikaans, for mid-teenagers, of explorer Charles John Andersson's epic mid-19th-Century trek from Walvis Bay to Lake Ngami.\n* Land of the Thirst King (1975{{snd}}reprinted 1979). Historical/contemporary travel book about Namaqualand (North-West Cape Province).\n* Adeus Angola (1976). First account of the initial South African military incursion into Angola (now a standard reference work).\n* The Soldiers (1978). Short interlinked biographies of Generals [[Christiaan de Wet]], [[Koos de la Rey]], Sir [[Henry Lukin|Henry Timson Lukin]], Sir [[Jacob van Deventer (general)|Jaap van Deventer]], [[Dan Pienaar]] and [[Evered Poole]]\n* Poor Man's Bioscope (1979). Historical/contemporary travel book about Cape Town\n*  Moedverloor (1980). Historical novel, in Afrikaans, about Great Namaqualand (now Namibia) in the 19th Century\n* S\u00ea vir Leonardo (1980). Contemporary action novel, in Afrikaans, set in Cape Town\n* Aircraft of the South African Air Force (1981). Illustrated survey of contemporary SAAF aircraft; later reprinted as Jane's Book of the SAAF (now a standard reference work)\n* Borderstrike! (1983). First detailed account of early South African military incursions into Angola, 1978\u20131980 (now a standard reference work). Expanded/re-edited edition 2003\n* Namakwalandse Oustories (1983). Re-telling, in Afrikaans, of traditional Namaqualand folk-tales\n* Christmas Story/Kersverhaal (1984). Re-telling of the Nativity, in separate English and Afrikaans versions, from the viewpoint of the animals in the stable\n* The Horse Thief (1985). Historical novel set in Namaqualand in the 1870s (winner of 1985 Lady Usher Memorial Prize, and later staged at Nico Malan Theatre, Cape Town)\n* Blake's Woman (1986). Historical novel set in 19th-Century Great Namaqualand (now Namibia)\n* The Blockhouse (1987). Historical novel set at the end of the Second Anglo-Boer War (co-winner of Maskew Miller Prize)\n* South Africa's Border War, 1966\u20131989 (1989). Illustrated history of the SWA/Namibian border war (now a standard reference work); due for facsimile reprint in 2014\n* Jim Zulu (2006). Historical novel set in the Kimberley diamond diggings area of the 1880s, inspired by South Africa's only known case of public lynching\n* Assegais, Drums and Dragoons (2012). The early military and social history of the Cape of Good Hope, 1510\u20131806  \n* The Black Beret: the history of the SA Armoured Corps, Volume 1 (early beginnings up to 842 Madagascar campaign) 2016)\n* SA's Border War 1966-1989 (revised and updated edition) (2016)\n* SA se Grensoorlog 1966-1989 (revised and updated edition) (2016)\n* Mobility Conquers: The Story Of 61 Mechanised Battalion Group 1978\u20132005, with Helmoed-R\u00f6mer Heitman (September 2016)\nWork in progress: Volume 2 of SAAC history (the Italian campaign)(scheduled for publication in 2017)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Author !! Type !! Genre !! Topic !! Year\n|-\n| Borderstrike! South Africa into Angola<ref name=borderstrike>{{cite book|last1=Steenkamp|first1=Willem|title=Borderstrike! South Africa into Angola. 1975\u20131980|year=2006|publisher=Just Done Productions Publishing|location=Durban, South Africa|isbn=978-1-920169-00-8|edition=3rd|url=http://www.justdone.co.za/shop/index.php?id_product=5&controller=product|accessdate=29 September 2014|publication-date = 1 March 2006}}</ref> || Willem Steenkamp || Non-Fiction || Military History || Military || 2006\n|-\n| Assegais, Drums & Dragoons: A Military and Social History of the Cape<ref>{{cite book|last1=Steenkamp|first1=Willem|title=Assegais, Drums & Dragoons: A Military and Social History of the Cape|publisher=Jonathon Ball|location=Cape Town, South Africa|isbn=9781868424795|url=http://jonathanball.bookslive.co.za/blog/2012/04/11/willem-steenkamp-brings-life-to-the-capes-history-in-assegais-drums-dragoons/|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First overall history of SA Infantry published|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/02f658804b86ca0988deac2a2f29c9df/First-overall-history-of-SA-Infantry-published-20120607|website=SABC|publisher=South African Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=5 October 2014|date=7 June 2012|quote=For the first time, a little-known chapter in the history of the South African Infantry has been brought to light with the publication of the first in a series of books dealing with the history of the \"Queen of Battles\"}}</ref