{"title_page": "Phaswane Mpe", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n'''Phaswane Mpe''' (10 September 1970 \u2013 12 December 2004) was a South African [[poet]] and [[novelist]].  He was educated at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]], where he was a lecturer in African literature. He did his Masters in Publishing at [[Oxford Brookes University]] in 1998.  His [[debut novel]], ''[[Welcome to Our Hillbrow]]'', was published in [[2001 in literature|2001]]. A collection of short stories and poems, ''Brooding Clouds'', was published posthumously in 2008.\n\nMpe was born in the northern city of [[Polokwane]] in Tiragalong,<ref>Mpe Phaswane. 2001. ''Welcome To Our Hillbrow''.</ref> and moved to [[Johannesburg]] at the age of 19 to attend university.  Due to his lack of money he ended up living in the deprived inner city area of [[Hillbrow]], a place where he later set his first novel.  ''Welcome to Our Hillbrow'' was an important work as it was the first novel to deal with the changes of inner-city life in South Africa in the ten years since [[Nelson Mandela]] and [[F. W. de Klerk]] engineered [[apartheid|apartheid's]] demise.  The book depicts the native black South Africans facing the challenges of poverty, unemployment, and [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]].  The novel is striking in that the problems created by apartheid are in the background; the central problems of black South Africans are those of their own making: xenophobia, mean-spirited gossip, witchcraft, and the inability to fully love each other or themselves.\n\nPerhaps unsurprisingly, considering the prevalence of the disease in South Africa, HIV and AIDS were common themes in Mpe's work. Before his death he embarked on doctorate studies on sexuality in post-apartheid South African literature with a particular focus on these two issues.\n\nMpe died suddenly at the age of 34, at the time he was about to begin training as a traditional [[healer (alternative medicine)|healer]].\n\nAt the time of his death Mpe was teaching African literature and publishing studies in the school of literature and languages studies in the University of the Witwatersrand. His poems and short stories have been published in ''Imprint'' (1995), ''Staff Rider'' (1980). He also contributed short stories in ''Drum Magazine.<ref>Mpe P. 2001. Welcome To Our Hillbrow.</ref>\n\nHis book ''Welcome to Our Hillbrow'', and short stories in ''Brooding Clouds'' have autobiographical information.<ref>Mpe, P. 2001. Welcome To Our Hillbrow</ref>\n''\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mpe, Phaswane}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Polokwane]]\n[[Category:Northern Sotho people]]\n[[Category:South African male novelists]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2012}}\n{{unreferenced|date=May 2011}}\n'''Phaswane Mpe''' (10 September 1970 \u2013 12 December 2004) was a South African [[poet]] and [[novelist]].  He was educated at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]], where he was a lecturer in African literature. He did his Masters in Publishing at [[Oxford Brookes University]] in 1998.  His [[debut novel]], ''[[Welcome to Our Hillbrow]]'', was published in [[2001 in literature|2001]]. A collection of short stories and poems, ''Brooding Clouds'', was published posthumously in 2008.\n\nMpe was born in the northern city of [[Polokwane]] in Tiragalong,<ref>Mpe Phaswane. 2001. ''Welcome To Our Hillbrow''.</ref> and moved to [[Johannesburg]] at the age of 19 to attend university.  Due to his lack of money he ended up living in the deprived inner city area of [[Hillbrow]], a place where he later set his first novel.  ''Welcome to Our Hillbrow'' was an important work as it was the first novel to deal with the changes of inner-city life in South Africa in the ten years since [[Nelson Mandela]] and [[F. W. de Klerk]] engineered [[apartheid|apartheid's]] demise.  The book depicts the native black South Africans facing the challenges of poverty, unemployment, and [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]].  The novel is striking in that the problems created by apartheid are in the background; the central problems of black South Africans are those of their own making: xenophobia, mean-spirited gossip, witchcraft, and the inability to fully love each other or themselves.\n\nPerhaps unsurprisingly, considering the prevalence of the disease in South Africa, HIV and AIDS were common themes in Mpe's work. Before his death he embarked on doctorate studies on sexuality in post-apartheid South African literature with a particular focus on these two issues.\n\nMpe died suddenly at the age of 34, at the time he was about to begin training as a traditional [[healer (alternative medicine)|healer]].\n\nAt the time of his death Mpe was teaching African literature and publishing studies in the school of literature and languages studies in the University of the Witwatersrand. His poems and short stories have been published in ''Imprint'' (1995), ''Staff Rider'' (1980). He also contributed short stories in ''Drum Magazine.<ref>Mpe P. 2001. Welcome To Our Hillbrow.</ref>\n\nHis book ''Welcome to Our Hillbrow'', and short stories in ''Brooding Clouds'' have autobiographical information.<ref>Mpe, P. 2001. Welcome To Our Hillbrow</ref>\n''\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mpe, Phaswane}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Polokwane]]\n[[Category:Northern Sotho people]]\n[[Category:South African male novelists]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phaswane_Mpe"}
